# Naming & Terminology Standards

## Function Names

All function verbs must be from the PowerShell approved verb list (`Get-Verb`). Common violations to avoid:

```powershell
# WRONG — Draw is not an approved verb
function Draw-MainFrame { ... }
function Draw-ResizeLogo { ... }
function Draw-DialogShadow { ... }

# CORRECT
function Write-MainFrame { ... }
function Write-ResizeLogo { ... }
function Write-DialogShadow { ... }
```

Nouns must be simple descriptive nouns, not prepositional phrases or adjective-qualified modes:

```powershell
# WRONG
function Get-ValueWithVariance { ... }   # prepositional phrase
function Write-ButtonImmediate { ... }   # adjective as noun qualifier

# CORRECT
function Get-VariedValue { ... }
function Write-MenuButton { ... }
```

Nested helper functions inside Private/ files use PascalCase matching the outer convention (`DrawCompleteScreen`, not `drawCompleteScreen`).

## Parameters

All parameters use PascalCase — no exceptions:

```powershell
# WRONG
param($x, $y, $width, $bgColor, $currentField, $errorMsg)

# CORRECT
param($X, $Y, $Width, $BackgroundColor, $CurrentField, $ErrorMessage)
```

## Variables

Names describe **what** the value is, not **how** it was obtained:

```powershell
# WRONG — describes the polling mechanism, not the state
$wasJustPressed

# CORRECT — describes what the value represents
$pressedSinceLastPoll
```

No single-letter names except for established geometric coordinates (`$X`, `$Y`) passed as a coordinate pair. No cryptic abbreviations:

```powershell
# WRONG
$ras       # binary direction selector
$math      # tick count
$GPS       # Group Policy settings hashtable
$xPath     # transcript file path (collides with XPath)
$sw        # window width
$sb        # StringBuilder
$c         # CSI escape prefix
$nw        # NoWrap flag
$ex        # exception variable

# CORRECT
$varianceSign
$ticksToWait
$groupPolicySettings
$transcriptPath
$windowWidth
$frameBuilder
$csi
$isNoWrap
$flushException
```

## `$_` Prefix Convention (CRITICAL)

The `$_` prefix is **reserved exclusively for provisioner-local variables** (`$_modPath`, `$_iss`, `$_rs`, `$_ps`, `$_kvp`). Never use `$_` for temporaries in the main function body — it creates a false impression that a variable is provisioner-scoped.

Documented architectural locals (`$_isViewerMode`, `$_viewerPipeClient`, `$_settingsEpoch`, etc.) are the only exceptions and are listed in AGENTS.md.

## User-Visible Strings

**No internal architecture terms in user-facing output.** Terms like "Worker", "Viewer", "pipe", "IPC", and "inline mode" are implementation details invisible to the user.

```powershell
# WRONG — exposes internal architecture
Show-Notification -Body "Worker started (PID: $PID)"
Show-Notification -Body "Viewer disconnected"

# CORRECT — speaks as the application
Show-Notification -Body "$($script:WindowTitle) started (PID: $PID)"
Show-Notification -Body "$($script:WindowTitle) — terminal disconnected"
```

**"Quit" is correct** for application controls (system tray, dialogs, menu labels). "Exit" is the older MDI File-menu convention and is not used in this codebase.

**Log entries** use sentence case, passive voice, and "via X" for source attribution — not parenthetical tags:

```powershell
# WRONG
" - Paused (hotkey)"
" - User input skip"
" - Coordinates updated"
" x$x/y$y"

# CORRECT
" - Paused via hotkey"
" - Skipped: user input detected"
" - Mouse position set"
" ($x, $y)"
```

**UI labels** use plain English with em-dash for empty/none states, and consistent sentence/title case:

```powershell
# WRONG
"(none)"   # in stats fields
"off"      # for disabled options
"DEBUGMODE"
" Update available!"  # exclamation mark

# CORRECT
[char]0x2014  # em-dash
"Disabled"
"Debug Mode"
" Update available"
```

**Menu buttons** use title case on the hotkey letter: `(S)ettings`, `(Q)uit`, `(I)ncognito`.

Em-dash (`—`) not double-hyphen (`--`) in prose strings.

## Comments

Comments state **what** a block is for in one line. Detailed architectural context belongs in `AGENTS.md`, not inline.

```powershell
# WRONG — narrates the code; detailed mechanics belong in AGENTS.md
# We use GetLastInputInfo here because it passively detects all system-wide
# input without requiring a message pump or global hook. The cbSize field
# must be set before calling...

# CORRECT — names the block
# System-wide input detection
```

No contractions (`do not`, not `don't`). No self-deprecating or editorial notes. Em-dash in comments, not double-hyphen.

`"jiggle"` / `"jiggling"` are not used as technical terms in code or comments — use "cursor movement" or "activity simulation". Flavor text (resize quotes, module header) is exempt.
